 ways that point to the changing practices of dispossession. In so doing, Sánchez and Pita prompt critics to reconsider the role of settler colonialism in the deep history of the United States and how spatial and discursive violence are always correlated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aIndians of North AmericaxColonizationzMexican-American Border Region. 0aLand settlementzSouthwestern States. 0aViolence in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh1 aPita, Beatrice, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021292zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478021292.jpg  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles